"Weimerskirch H., Inchausti P., Guinet C., Barbraud C.","Trends in bird and seal populations as indicators of a system shift in the Southern Ocean",2003,"Antarctic Science","15","2",,"249","256",,,10.1017/S0954102003001202,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0038581676&partnerID=40&md5=ed8fd4099a63a9c622e3dde05f8ff4d8","Ctr. d'Etud. Biologiques de Chize, Ctr. Natl. de la Rech. Scientifique, F-79360 Villiers en Bois, France; Laboratoire d'Ecologie, Ecole Normale Supérieure, 17 rue d'Ulm, F-75005 Paris, France","Weimerskirch, H., Ctr. d'Etud. Biologiques de Chize, Ctr. Natl. de la Rech. Scientifique, F-79360 Villiers en Bois, France; Inchausti, P., Laboratoire d'Ecologie, Ecole Normale Supérieure, 17 rue d'Ulm, F-75005 Paris, France; Guinet, C., Ctr. d'Etud. Biologiques de Chize, Ctr. Natl. de la Rech. Scientifique, F-79360 Villiers en Bois, France; Barbraud, C., Ctr. d'Etud. Biologiques de Chize, Ctr. Natl. de la Rech. Scientifique, F-79360 Villiers en Bois, France","Although world oceans have been warming over the past 50 years, the impact on biotic components is poorly understood because of the difficulty of obtaining long-term datasets on marine organisms. The Southern Ocean plays a critical role in global climate and there is growing evidence of climate warming. We show that air temperatures measured by meteorological stations have steadily increased over the past 50 years in the southern Indian Ocean, the increase starting in mid 1960s and stabilizing in mid 1980s, being particularly important in the sub-Antarctic sector. At the same time, with a time lag of 2-9 years with temperatures, the population size of most seabirds and seals monitored on several breeding sites have decreased severely, whilst two species have increased at the same time. These changes, together with indications of a simultaneous decrease in secondary production in sub-Antarctic waters and the reduction of sea-ice extent further south, indicate that a major system shift has occurred in the Indian Ocean part of the Southern Ocean. This shift illustrates the high sensitivity of marine ecosystems, and especially upper trophic level predators, to climatic changes.","Antarctic; Global warming; Sea-ice; Seabirds; Seals; Sub-Antarctic","bird; climate change; global warming; mammal; population dynamics; population ecology; Southern Ocean; Aves; Mammalia; Phocidae",,,,,,"Aebischer, N.J., Coulson, J.C., Colebrook, J.M., Parallel long-term trends across four marine trophic levels and weather (1990) Nature, 347, pp. 753-755; Ainley, D.G., Divoky, G.J., Birds, seabirds responses to climate change Encyclopaedia of Ocean Sciences, , In press. London: Academic Press; Barbraud, C., Weimerskirch, H., Emperor penguins and climate change (2001) Nature, 411, pp. 183-186; Boyd, I., Walker, T.R., Poncet, J., Status of southern elephant seals at South Georgia (1996) Antarctic Science, 8, pp. 237-244; Brothers, N., Albatross mortality and associated bait loss in the Japanese longline fishery in the Southern Ocean (1991) Biological Conservation, 55, pp. 255-268; Cherel, Y., Klages, N., A review of the food of albatrosses (1998) Albatross Biology and Conservation, pp. 113-136. , Robertson, G. & Gales, R., ed. Chipping Norton: Surrey Beatty & Sons; Cherel, Y., Ridoux, V., Prey species and nutritive value of food fed during summer to king penguin Aptenodytes patagonica chicks at Possession Island, Crozet Archipelago (1992) Ibis, 134, pp. 118-127; Croxall, J.P., Southern Ocean environmental changes, effects on seabird, seal and whale populations (1992) Philosophical Transactions Royal Society London, B338, pp. 319-328; Croxall, J.P., Trathan, P.N., Murphy, E.J., Environmental change and Antarctic seabird populations (2002) Science, 297, pp. 1510-1514; Croxall, J.P., Prince, P.A., Rothery, P., Wood, A.G., Population changes in albatrosses at South Georgia (1998) Albatross Biology and Conservation, pp. 69-83. , Robertson, G. & Gales, R., ed. Chipping Norton: Surrey B